A4.text: When Google was a Stanford research project, it was nicknamed BackRub because the technology checks backlinks to determine a site's importance.

A5.text: When Google was a Stanford research project, it was nicknamed BackRub.

A6.text: The rapid growth of their project caused Stanford's computing infrastructure to experience problems.

A7.text: The initial version of Google, still on the Stanford University website, was made available to Internet users in August 1996.

A8.text: As their search engine grew in popularity among Stanford users, it required additional servers to process the queries.

A9.text: BackRub already exhibited the rudimentary functions and characteristics of a search engine: a query input was entered and it provided a list of backlinks ranked by importance.
